  "local_port": 58130,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Do I need a lawyer prepared NDA when talking to product design & manufacturing consultants? Will a template off the internet work just as well?",
  "response": "While using a template for a Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) can be a viable option, there are several factors to consider when deciding whether to customize one or consult with a lawyer:\n\n1. **Complexity of Information**: If the information you plan to share is confidential and critical to your business (e.g., trade secrets, proprietary designs), it may be worth having a lawyer draft or review an NDA to ensure it adequately protects your interests.\n\n2. **Jurisdiction**: Laws regarding NDAs can vary significantly by jurisdiction, and a template may not be compliant with your local laws or the laws that govern your relationship with the consultants.\n\n3. **Specificity**: A generic template may not cover specific situations or nuances of your relationship or the information being shared. A lawyer can help tailor the agreement to include specific clauses relevant to your needs.\n\n4. **Enforceability**: A poorly drafted NDA can be unenforceable. A lawyer can ensure that the language used in the NDA is clear and legally binding.\n\n5. **Scope and Term**: A lawyer can help you define the scope of the NDA (what information is considered confidential) and the term (how long the information remains confidential) appropriately.\n\n6. **Future Considerations**: If your project is likely to evolve, a lawyer can help you draft terms that are adaptable to future developments.\n\nIn summary, while an internet template can serve as a starting point, consulting with a lawyer is generally recommended for important legal documents like an NDA, especially when sensitive information is involved. This way, you can ensure that your interests are fully protected.",
